Overleden","1174–Female":"1174–Overleden","abt 1204":"circa 1204","1204":"1204","1174":"1174","1240":"1240","about 1240":"circa 1240","1208":"1208","Gower, Glamorgan, Wales":"Gower, Glamorgan, Wales","of Gower, Glmrgn, Wls":"Gower, Glamorgan, Wales"},"en":{"abt 1204–":"about 1204–Deceased","1204–Male":"1204–Deceased","1208–Female":"1208–Deceased","1240–Male":"1240–Deceased","1174–Female":"1174–Deceased","abt 1204":"about 1204","1204":"1204","1174":"1174","1240":"1240","about 1240":"about 1240","1208":"1208","Gower, Glamorgan, Wales":"Gower, Glamorgan, Wales","of Gower, Glmrgn, Wls":"Gower, Glamorgan, Wales","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Ivor","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English: (i) relationship name from Old Scandinavian  <i>Ívarr</i>,  <i>Iwar</i>,  <i>Ivar</i> ‘yew-army’. (ii) relationship name, possibly from the Welsh male given name  <i>Ifor</i>; if so, it is not clear that it survives today."],"variants":[{"name":"Ivers","meanings":["Irish: from <b>Ó hÍomhair</b>, ‘descendant of <i>Íomhar</i>’, a Gaelic form of the Old Norse personal name <i>Ívarr</i> (see   Iverson   2), with excrescent English <i>-s</i>. It is occasionally Anglicized as   Howard  . Also a shortened form of <b>Mac Íomhair</b> ‘son of <i>Íomhar</i>’, with excrescent English <i>-s</i>. See   McIver  .","North German: patronymic from the personal name <i>Ivar</i> (see   Iversen  ).","English: variant of <b>Iver</b>, with post-medieval excrescent <i>-s</i>, a habitational name from Iver (Buckinghamshire) named from Old English <i>ȳfre</i> ‘edge or brow of a hill, tip of a promontory’, or from a minor place called with the same word."]},{"name":"Iver","meanings":["1  English: locative name from Iver (Bucks) named from Old English * <i>ȳfre</i> ‘edge or brow of a hill, tip of a promontory’, or from a minor place named with the same word.","2  Scottish: (i) relationship name, reduced form of Irish and Scottish Gaelic  <b>Mac Íomhair</b>,  see  McIvor  . (ii) relationship name from the Old Scandinavian personal name  <i>Ivar</i>;  see  Ivor  ."]},{"name":"Iverson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Scandinavian Iver, Erik, Hjalmer, Lars, Selmer, Thor, Evald, Gunner, Helmer, Ingman, Jarl, Joneen.","Americanized form of Norwegian, Danish, and North German   Iversen   and of Swedish <b>Ivarsson</b> (see   Ivarson  ), all cognates of 2 below.","English (Kent and London): patronymic from Old Norse <i>Ívarr</i>, <i>Iwar</i>, <i>Ivar</i>, a compound of either <i>ív</i> ‘yew tree, bow’ or <i>Ing</i> (the name of a god) + <i>ar</i> ‘warrior’ or ‘spear’. Alternatively, the name might be a patronymic from the Welsh male personal name <i>Ifor</i>, itself from British Celtic <i>Iūdomāros</i> ‘lord’ + ‘great’, but if so, it is not clear that it survives today."]}]},{"name":"Ynyr","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Traditional: pronounced ‘<b>inn</b>-eer’, probably from the Latin name <i>Honorius</i> (a derivative of <i>honor</i> ‘renown’)."],"variants":[]},{"name":"ap","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["‘Loving’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Ynyr ap Ivor was born about 1204, in Gower, Glamorgan, Wales as the son of Mrs. Ivor ap Richard. He had at least 1 son with Mrs. Ynyr ap Ivor."},"et":{"abt 1204–":"umbes 1204–Surnud","1204–Male":"1204–Surnud","1208–Female":"1208–Surnud","1240–Male":"1240–Surnud","1174–Female":"1174–Surnud","abt 1204":"umbes 1204","1204":"1204","1174":"1174","1240":"1240","about 1240":"umbes 1240","1208":"1208","Gower, Glamorgan, Wales":"Gower, Glamorgan, Wales","of Gower, Glmrgn, Wls":"Gower, Glamorgan, Wales"},"fi":{"abt 1204–":"noin 1204–Kuollut","1204–Male":"1204–Kuollut","1208–Female":"1208–Kuollut","1240–Male":"1240–Kuollut","1174–Female":"1174–Kuollut","abt 1204":"